######################################
######### Embedded declaratives ######
######################################

# 1. "ta" complement clauses."Ta" complement clauses must be finite: 
# co-referential arguments are not deleted in the complement clause.
# To use "ta" with verbs, it is used with certain imperative verbs,
#  i.e. aguray `wait`, ibaga `tell`, umay `come`, etc

# week 4
# imperative + ta + declarative clause
Source: a:462
Vetted: s
Judgment: g
Phenomena: {Embedded declaratives}
Aguraykayo     ta  sapulek
ag-uray=ka     ta  sapul-en=ko
I-wait=ABS.2SG SUB search-T=ERG.1SG.(3SG)
`Wait and I'll look for it`

# ungrammatical: co-referential argument is deleted
Source: a:462
Vetted: s
Judgment: g
Phenomena: {Embedded declaratives}
Aguraykayo     ta  sapulek
ag-uray=ka     ta  sapul-en
I-wait=ABS.2SG SUB search-T
`Wait and I'll look for it`

# 2. In another case, complement clauses are preceded by Ligature, "(ng)a".
# Co-refential arguments may be expressed twice: once in the main clause,
# and again in the complement clause for clarity (to avoid any ambiguity.
# Week 4
Source: a:468
Vetted: s
Judgment: g
Phenomena: {Embedded declaratives}
Ikariko           a   mapanak
i-kari=ko         a   ma-pan=ak
T-promise=ERG.1SG LIG I-go=ABS.1SG
`I promise to go (I promise that I go)`

# Week 4
Source: a:242
Vetted: s
Judgment: g
Phenomena: {Embedded declaratives}
Ammok        a   nakitamo         ti      lalaki
ammo=ko      a   na-kita=mo       ti      lalaki
know=ERG.1SG LIG PF.T-see=ERG.2SG CORE.SG boy
`I know that you saw the boy`

# ungrammatical: ligature complementizer takes finite clause only
Source: author
Vetted: f
Judgment: u
Phenomena: {Embedded declaratives}
Ammok        a   ti      lalaki
ammo=ko      a   ti      lalaki
know=ERG.1SG LIG CORE.SG boy
`I know that you saw the boy`


