`The house is clean`

# Week 4
# Prepositional phrase (via oblique noun phrase)
Source: a:416
Vetted: s
Judgment: g
Phenomena: {Non-verbal predicates}
Iti    rabaw ti      lamisaan ti      tulbek
iti    rabaw ti      lamisaan ti      tulbek
OBL.SG top   CORE.SG table    CORE.SG key
`The key is on the table`


######################################
######### POSSESSIVE #################
######################################

# Ilocano pronominal possesives, such as 'my', 'their, 'your', etc,
# are achieved by the use of a noun with an enclitic pronoun in ergative
# case.
# From page 117:
# Normally, a possessor follows the possessed referent. possessive constructions are done
# simply by juxtaposing possessum and possessor. A possessor may be encoded with a full noun
# phrase (the appropriate article introducing the relevant nominal possessor) or an ergative enclitic
# pronoun.

# grammatically correct possessive, using ergative enclitic pronoun
Source: a:117
Vetted: s
Judgment: g
Phenomena: {possessives}
Nakita   ti      babai ti      balayko
na-kita  ti      babai ti      balay=ko
PF.T-see CORE.SG girl  CORE.SG house=ERG.1sg
`The girl saw my house'

# from p.384:
# possession in Ilocano can be expressed by simple juxtaposition of
# the possessed entity and possessor. in that order.
Source: a:117
Vetted: s
Judgment: g
Phenomena: {possessives}
Nakitako         ti      tulbek ti      lalaki
na-kita=ko       ti      tulbek ti      lalaki
PF.T-see=1SG.ERG CORE.SG key    CORE.SG boy
`I saw the boy's key'

# Though cannot find exact source, goal focus verb with core NP as subject,
# followed by the possesum NP and possessor NP seems theoretically possible
Source: author
Vetted: f
Judgment: g
Phenomena: {possessives}
Nakita   ti      babai ti      tulbek ti      lalaki
na-kita  ti      babai ti      tulbek ti      lalaki
PF.T-see CORE.SG girl  CORE.SG key    CORE.SG boy
`The girl saw the boy's key'

# incorrect case for possessive, using absolutive enclitic pronoun
Source: author
Vetted: f
Judgment: u
Phenomena: {case}
Nakita   ti      babai ti      balayak
na-kita  ti      babai ti      balay=ak
PF.T-see CORE.SG girl  CORE.SG house=ABS.1sg
`The girl saw my house'

# possessive nominal needs CORE.SG determiner before the 3rdPerson noun
Source: author
Vetted: f
Judgment: u
Phenomena: {case}
Nakita   ti      babai balayak
na-kita  ti      babai balay=ak
PF.T-see CORE.SG girl  house=ABS.1sg
`The girl saw my house'

# Example from page a:117 but substituted a person's name (ni Maria) with a noun (ti babai)
# This is the case where two NPs are juxtaposed
Source: a:117
Vetted: f
Judgment: g
Phenomena: {possessives}
nakitako         ti      baiay ti      babai
na-kita=ko       ti      baiay ti      babai
PF.T-see=1SG.ERG CORE.SG house CORE.SG girl
'I saw the girl's house'

# This is the case where tww NPs are juxtaposed but for actor focus, the object is
# in the oblique case, followed by the possessor, which needs to be in core case
Source: author
Vetted: f
Judgment: g
Phenomena: {possessives}
nagkitaak        iti    baiay ti      babai
n-ag-kita=ak     iti    baiay ti      babai
PF-I-see=1SG.ABS OBL.SG house CORE.SG girl
'I saw the girl's house'

# two oblique case juxtaposed is not describing possessives
Source: author
Vetted: f
Judgment: u
Phenomena: {possessives}
nagkitaak        iti     baiay iti    babai
n-ag-kita=ak     iti     baiay iti    babai
PF-I-see=1SG.ABS CORE.SG house OBL.SG girl
'I saw the girl's house'


######################################
######### TENSE / ASPECT / MOOD ######
######################################

# Correct affixation of perfective aspect marker n-
Source: a:186
Vetted: f
Judgment: g
Phenomena: {tam}
Naglaylay   ti      sabong
n-ag-laylay ti      sabong
PF-I-wilt   CORE.SG flower.ABS
‘The flower wilted’

# Correct infixation of perfective aspect marker -in- 
# (which, when combining with its corresponding “intransitive” 
# infix -um-, becomes -imm-)
Source: author
Vetted: f
Judgment: g
Phenomena: {tam}
Timmarayak
taray-{um}-{in}=ak
run-{I}-{PF}=ABS.1SG
‘I ran’

# Correct reduplication of first (C)VC of verb stem, 
# indicating imperfective aspect
Source: author
Vetted: f
Judgment: g
Phenomena: {tam}
Agbasbasa        ti      ansisit
ag-basa-RR       ti      ansisit
PF.I-read-IMPERF CORE.SG dwarf
‘The dwarf reads’

# Incorrect co-occurrence of n- perfective aspect marker with incompatible -um- infix
Source: author
Vetted: f
Judgement: u
Phenomena: {tam}
Numumanges     ti      lalaki
n-umanges-{um} ti      lalaki
PF-breathe-{I} CORE.SG boy
`The boy breathed`



